itical power it has had either in the popular understanding or in the corruption of constitutional ideals unless many new immigrants, themselves often regarded as racially inferior, had been drawn into accepting and supporting many of the terms of American racism. With its unprecedented focus on Italian American identity and an interdisciplinary approach to comparative culture and law, this timely study sheds important light on the history and contemporary importance of identity and multicultural politics in American political and constitutional debate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aAmericanization. 0aConstitutional historyzEurope. 0aConstitutional historyzItaly. 0aConstitutional historyzUnited States. 0aItalian AmericansxCultural assimilation. 0aItalian AmericansxEthnic identity. 0aRacismxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aRacismxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479849048423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781479849048.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK